estid="og" srcSet="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*0myhgmQjyYoHs9eUzOjijQ.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*0myhgmQjyYoHs9eUzOjijQ.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*0myhgmQjyYoHs9eUzOjijQ.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*0myhgmQjyYoHs9eUzOjijQ.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*0myhgmQjyYoHs9eUzOjijQ.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*0myhgmQjyYoHs9eUzOjijQ.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*0myhgmQjyYoHs9eUzOjijQ.png 1400w" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px"/><img alt="" class="bd md nj c" width="700" height="467" loading="eager" role="presentation"/></picture></div></div><figcaption class="nk fj nl mw mx nm nn bb b bc u dy">Processing 1 millions transactions in under a second using GO.</figcaption></figure><p id="7f2c" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg">It’s Black Friday. Millions of shoppers are flooding an e-commerce platform, buying everything from 75-inch TVs to phone chargers they’ll lose in a week. Meanwhile, somewhere in a dimly lit office, an analytics team is frantically refreshing dashboards, waiting for insights that never seem to arrive.</p><p id="c527" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg">What if we could process 1 million transactions in under a second? Not with a cluster of GPUs or Kafka streams. Just Go.</p><p id="5937" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg">We’ll start with the simplest possible solution, watch it fail badly, then work through exactly why it fails and how to fix it. By the end, you’ll have a clear mental model of Go’s concurrency model, batch processing, worker pools, and what actually moves the needle on performance.</p><h2 id="644a" class="om on ho bb oo op oq or os ot ou ov ow ox oy oz pa pb pc pd pe pf pg ph pi pj bg">The Challenge</h2><p id="7ee9" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr pk nt nu nv pl nx ny nz pm ob oc od pn of og oh po oj ok ol hh bg">We want to build a transaction processing system that handles massive volumes of e-commerce data quickly. Each transaction looks like this:</p><pre class="pp pq pr ps pt pu pv pw bl px ax bg"><span id="820c" class="py on ho pv b bc pz qa e qb qc">{<br/>  &quot;order_id&quot;: &quot;order_12345&quot;,<br/>  &quot;user_id&quot;: &quot;user_789&quot;,<br/>  &quot;product_id&quot;: &quot;laptop_pro_256&quot;,<br/>  &quot;quantity&quot;: 2,<br/>  &quot;price&quot;: 1299.99,<br/>  &quot;timestamp&quot;: &quot;2024-10-21T15:04:05Z&quot;<br/>}</span></pre><p id="d23e" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg"><strong class="nq hp">The goal</strong>: process 1 million of these in under a second while tracking analytics like user spending totals and order volumes. No GPU cluster, no message queue. Just a single Go process.</p><p id="d2da" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg">That’s the bar. Let’s see how far the naive approach gets us.</p><blockquote class="qd qe qf"><p id="c269" class="no np qg nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg">A note on benchmarks: TPS figures throughout this article were measured on a MacBook Pro M2 Pro against a local PostgreSQL instance. Your numbers will differ depending on hardware and database setup. What matters is the relative improvement between approaches, not the exact number.</p></blockquote><h2 id="a587" class="om on ho bb oo op oq or os ot ou ov ow ox oy oz pa pb pc pd pe pf pg ph pi pj bg">The Naive Approach</h2><p id="67ad" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr pk nt nu nv pl nx ny nz pm ob oc od pn of og oh po oj ok ol hh bg">Let’s start with the most obvious solution: read the file line by line and write each transaction to the database.</p><pre class="pp pq pr ps pt pu pv pw bl px ax bg"><span id="4854" class="py on ho pv b bc pz qa e qb qc">func processTransactions(filename string) error {<br/>    file, err := os.Open(filename)<br/>    if err != nil {<br/>        return err<br/>    }<br/>    defer file.Close()<br/><br/>    scanner := bufio.NewScanner(file)<br/>    for scanner.Scan() {<br/>        var tx Transaction<br/>        if err := json.Unmarshal([]byte(scanner.Text()), &amp;tx); err != nil {<br/>            continue<br/>        }<br/>        updateDatabase(tx)<br/>    }<br/>    return scanner.Err()<br/>}</span></pre><p id="5699" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg">Simple, readable, and correct. Let’s run it on 1 million records.</p><p id="53fe" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg"><strong class="nq hp">Result: ~350 TPS.</strong></p><p id="a88d" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg">At that rate, 1 million records takes roughly 47 minutes. We needed 0.5 seconds. We’re only off by a factor of 5,704. No big deal! 😅</p><figure class="pp pq pr ps pt ne"><div class="qh ge e fv"><div class="qi qj e"></div></div></figure><h2 id="8411" class="om on ho bb oo op oq or os ot ou ov ow ox oy oz pa pb pc pd pe pf pg ph pi pj bg">Why It’s So Slow</h2><p id="1727" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr pk nt nu nv pl nx ny nz pm ob oc od pn of og oh po oj ok ol hh bg">Four things are working against us:</p><ol class=""><li id="589c" class="no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol qk ql qm bg"><strong class="nq hp">Single-threaded processing.</strong> We’re using one core on a machine that likely has several sitting idle.</li><li id="dd23" class="no np ho nq b nr qn nt nu nv qo nx ny nz qp ob oc od qq of og oh qr oj ok ol qk ql qm bg"><strong class="nq hp">A million individual database calls.</strong> Each one has query overhead, network round trips, and execution cost.</li><li id="2055" class="no np ho nq b nr qn nt nu nv qo nx ny nz qp ob oc od qq of og oh qr oj ok ol qk ql qm bg"><strong class="nq hp">No batching.</strong> Every transaction is treated as a separate unit of work.</li><li id="49a0" class="no np ho nq b nr qn nt nu nv qo nx ny nz qp ob oc od qq of og oh qr oj ok ol qk ql qm bg"><strong class="nq hp">Sequential I/O.</strong> We read a line, parse it, update analytics, write to the database, then repeat.</li></ol><figure class="pp pq pr ps pt ne mw mx paragraph-image"><div role="button" tabindex="0" class="nf ng fv nh bd ni"><span class="ga gb gc ai gd ge gf fo gg speechify-ignore">Press enter or click to view image in full size</span><div class="mw mx qs"><picture><source srcSet="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*3CXM5-w60IdvkKky1vp2ZA.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*3CXM5-w60IdvkKky1vp2ZA.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*3CXM5-w60IdvkKky1vp2ZA.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*3CXM5-w60IdvkKky1vp2ZA.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*3CXM5-w60IdvkKky1vp2ZA.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*3CXM5-w60IdvkKky1vp2ZA.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/1*3CXM5-w60IdvkKky1vp2ZA.png 1400w" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" srcSet="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*3CXM5-w60IdvkKky1vp2ZA.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*3CXM5-w60IdvkKky1vp2ZA.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*3CXM5-w60IdvkKky1vp2ZA.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*3CXM5-w60IdvkKky1vp2ZA.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*3CXM5-w60IdvkKky1vp2ZA.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*3CXM5-w60IdvkKky1vp2ZA.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*3CXM5-w60IdvkKky1vp2ZA.png 1400w" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px"/><img alt="" class="bd md nj c" width="700" height="314" loading="lazy" role="presentation"/></picture></div></div></figure><p id="ebc8" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg">The important thing to notice is that these are not all the same kind of bottleneck.</p><ul class=""><li id="b441" class="no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol qt ql qm bg">File reading and database writes are I/O-bound.</li><li id="75f1" class="no np ho nq b nr qn nt nu nv qo nx ny nz qp ob oc od qq of og oh qr oj ok ol qt ql qm bg">JSON parsing and in-memory aggregation are CPU-bound.</li></ul><p id="24dc" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg">Different bottlenecks respond to different fixes. Instead of trying to make one giant sequential loop <em class="qg">faster</em>, we need to separate the pipeline and optimize each stage on its own terms.</p><h2 id="8872" class="om on ho bb oo op oq or os ot ou ov ow ox oy oz pa pb pc pd pe pf pg ph pi pj bg">Decoupling Reading from Processing</h2><p id="4ab0" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr pk nt nu nv pl nx ny nz pm ob oc od pn of og oh po oj ok ol hh bg">The first improvement is to stop treating file reading and transaction processing as one sequential block.</p><p id="9a5f" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg">If we separate them with a channel, the file reader can continue feeding work while another goroutine consumes it.</p><pre class="pp pq pr ps pt pu pv pw bl px ax bg"><span id="5531" class="py on ho pv b bc pz qa e qb qc">func betterProcessing(filename string) error {<br/>    lines := make(chan string, 1000)<br/><br/>    go func() {<br/>        file, err := os.Open(filename)<br/>        if err != nil {<br/>            close(lines)<br/>            return<br/>        }<br/>        defer file.Close()<br/><br/>        scanner := bufio.NewScanner(file)<br/>        for scanner.Scan() {<br/>            lines &lt;- scanner.Text()<br/>        }<br/>        close(lines)<br/>    }()<br/><br/>    for line := range lines {<br/>        var tx Transaction<br/>        if err := json.Unmarshal([]byte(line), &amp;tx); err != nil {<br/>            continue<br/>        }<br/>        updateDatabase(tx)<br/>    }<br/>    return nil<br/>}</span></pre><p id="9e32" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg">Let’s test that.</p><p id="ca22" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg"><strong class="nq hp">Result: ~400 TPS</strong></p><p id="6d90" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg">That’s better, but barely. The reader and processor now overlap, but we’re still hitting the database once per transaction. That’s still a million individual writes.</p><p id="80c1" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg">Pipelining helps, but pipelining alone doesn’t solve the real bottleneck.</p><p id="1509" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg">A quick note on channel buffer size: too small and the producer stalls; too large and you retain more data in memory than necessary. In practice, a buffer somewhere around 1,000 to 10,000 is a reasonable starting point for this kind of workload.</p><h2 id="1582" class="om on ho bb oo op oq or os ot ou ov ow ox oy oz pa pb pc pd pe pf pg ph pi pj bg">Adding Multiple Workers</h2><p id="130d" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr pk nt nu nv pl nx ny nz pm ob oc od pn of og oh po oj ok ol hh bg">The channel version gave us pipeline parallelism, but we still have a single goroutine doing all the processing.</p><p id="6c35" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg">If we spawn multiple workers reading from the same channel, Go’s scheduler can spread that work across multiple CPU cores.</p><pre class="pp pq pr ps pt pu pv pw bl px ax bg"><span id="c27a" class="py on ho pv b bc pz qa e qb qc">func workerPoolVersion(filename string, workerCount int) error {<br/>    lines := make(chan string, 10000)<br/>    var wg sync.WaitGroup<br/><br/>    for i := 0; i &lt; workerCount; i++ {<br/>        wg.Add(1)<br/>        go func() {<br/>            defer wg.Done()<br/>            for line := range lines {<br/>                var tx Transaction<br/>                if err := json.Unmarshal([]byte(line), &amp;tx); err != nil {<br/>                    continue<br/>                }<br/>                updateDatabase(tx)<br/>            }<br/>        }()<br/>    }<br/><br/>    go func() {<br/>        file, err := os.Open(filename)<br/>        if err != nil {<br/>            close(lines)<br/>            return<br/>        }<br/>        defer file.Close()<br/><br/>        scanner := bufio.NewScanner(file)<br/>        for scanner.Scan() {<br/>            lines &lt;- scanner.Text()<br/>        }<br/>        close(lines)<br/>    }()<br/><br/>    wg.Wait()<br/>    return nil<br/>}</span></pre><p id="95f4" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg">With 8 workers:</p><p id="0f1d" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg"><strong class="nq hp">Result: ~1,700 TPS.</strong></p><figure class="pp pq pr ps pt ne mw mx paragraph-image"><div role="button" tabindex="0" class="nf ng fv nh bd ni"><span class="ga gb gc ai gd ge gf fo gg speechify-ignore">Press enter or click to view image in full size</span><div class="mw mx qs"><picture><source srcSet="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*E394XVz-aIDye3JqSYoxoA.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*E394XVz-aIDye3JqSYoxoA.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*E394XVz-aIDye3JqSYoxoA.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*E394XVz-aIDye3JqSYoxoA.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*E394XVz-aIDye3JqSYoxoA.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*E394XVz-aIDye3JqSYoxoA.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/1*E394XVz-aIDye3JqSYoxoA.png 1400w" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" srcSet="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*E394XVz-aIDye3JqSYoxoA.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*E394XVz-aIDye3JqSYoxoA.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*E394XVz-aIDye3JqSYoxoA.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*E394XVz-aIDye3JqSYoxoA.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*E394XVz-aIDye3JqSYoxoA.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*E394XVz-aIDye3JqSYoxoA.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*E394XVz-aIDye3JqSYoxoA.png 1400w" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px"/><img alt="" class="bd md nj c" width="700" height="338" loading="lazy" role="presentation"/></picture></div></div></figure><p id="4c0f" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg">That’s about a 5x improvement just from parallelism alone.</p><p id="5b1a" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg">But we’re still nowhere near the target, because the design still performs a database operation for every transaction. Multiple workers help parse faster, but they do not change the cost model of a million round trips.</p><h2 id="63de" class="om on ho bb oo op oq or os ot ou ov ow ox oy oz pa pb pc pd pe pf pg ph pi pj bg">Batching Database Writes</h2><p id="f021" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr pk nt nu nv pl nx ny nz pm ob oc od pn of og oh po oj ok ol hh bg">Every database call has overhead: query parsing, transaction work, execution, network round trip. Even if a single insert is fast, doing it a million times is not.</p><div class="qu qv qw qx v j cs"><div class="qy qz ra rb rc e fj"><h2 class="rd b re rf rg rh ri">Get <!-- -->Kennedy Karoko<!-- -->’s stories in your inbox</h2></div><div class="cp e fj"><p class="bb b bc u dy">Join Medium for free to get updates from this writer.</p></div><div class="rm rn ro rp rq rr v"><span class="bb b bc u bg"><div class="rs v cs"><div class="v rs fg ff bl rt ru db lq rv rw rx ry rz sa sb"><input class="sc af ac ah sd se gg le bh sf bd" placeholder="Enter your email" type="text" value=""/></div></div></span><div class="au bt sg bx"><div class="rj rk rl"><button class="bb b bc u sh si sj sk sl sm sn ez fa so sp sq fe ff fg fh bi fi fj">Subscribe</button></div></div><div class="bd by r s"><button class="bb b bc u sh si sj sk sl sm sn ez fa so sp sq fe bd ff fg fh bi fi fj">Subscribe</button></div></div><div class="sr e"><label class="v j"><div class="th ti tj v tk bx fv"><input class="ss st su ga sv sw sx sy sz ta tb tc" type="checkbox" checked=""/><span class="j td te ff fg tf fh sh ak v sj tg cf" data-checkbox="true"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="11" height="11" viewBox="0 0 11 11" class="sj"><path d="m0 6.313 3.704 3.705.904.904.66-1.095 5.296-8.795L8.85 0 3.554 8.795l1.563-.191-3.704-3.705z"></path></svg></span></div><div class="e"><p class="bb b bc u bg">Remember me for faster sign in</p></div></label></div><div class="tl e"><div id="g-recaptcha"></div></div></div><p id="57df" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr nt nu nv nx ny nz ob oc od of og oh oj ok qx ol hh bg">The next fix is to stop writing one row at a time. Instead, accumulate work in memory and flush it in batches.</p><pre class="pp pq pr ps pt pu pv pw bl px ax bg"><span id="baf4" class="py on ho pv b bc pz qa e qb qc">func batchProcessing(lines &lt;-chan string, batchSize int) error {<br/>    var batch []Transaction<br/><br/>    for line := range lines {<br/>        var tx Transaction<br/>        if err := json.Unmarshal([]byte(line), &amp;tx); err != nil {<br/>            continue<br/>        }<br/><br/>        batch = append(batch, tx)<br/><br/>        if len(batch) &gt;= batchSize {<br/>            if err := processBatch(batch); err != nil {<br/>                return err<br/>            }<br/>            batch = batch[:0] // reset length, keep underlying array<br/>        }<br/>    }<br/><br/>    if len(batch) &gt; 0 {<br/>        return processBatch(batch)<br/>    }<br/><br/>    return nil<br/>}</span></pre><p id="520c" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg">The <code class="db tm tn to pv b">batch = batch[:0]</code> is worth calling out. It resets the slice length to zero while keeping the same underlying array, so the next batch can reuse the existing allocation instead of allocating fresh memory every time.</p><p id="364b" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg">Batch size is a tuning knob:</p><ul class=""><li id="d5f0" class="no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol qt ql qm bg">Too small and you still make too many database calls.</li><li id="b85c" class="no np ho nq b nr qn nt nu nv qo nx ny nz qp ob oc od qq of og oh qr oj ok ol qt ql qm bg">Too large and you hold more in memory than necessary, and failures affect larger chunks of work.</li></ul><p id="eb20" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg">In practice, 500 to 1,000 is a good starting range. Benchmark it on your own machine instead of guessing.</p><h2 id="3413" class="om on ho bb oo op oq or os ot ou ov ow ox oy oz pa pb pc pd pe pf pg ph pi pj bg">Worker-Local Aggregation Beats Shared State</h2><p id="3156" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr pk nt nu nv pl nx ny nz pm ob oc od pn of og oh po oj ok ol hh bg">At this point we have multiple workers consuming transactions concurrently. The next question is where analytics state should live.</p><p id="a729" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg">A common first instinct is to put all per-user analytics in one shared map and protect it with a mutex. That is correct, but under load it turns shared state into a bottleneck.</p><p id="fe32" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg">Even if you get fancier with per-user locks, you’re still paying synchronization cost in the hot path.</p><p id="76f5" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg">A better approach is to avoid shared-state contention during processing entirely.</p><p id="30e2" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg">Instead of having every worker update one global analytics map, let each worker own its own private map.</p><pre class="pp pq pr ps pt pu pv pw bl px ax bg"><span id="8d43" class="py on ho pv b bc pz qa e qb qc">type UserAnalytics struct {<br/> UserID      string<br/> TotalOrders int<br/> TotalSpent  float64<br/>}<br/>type Processor struct {<br/> workerMaps map[int]map[string]*UserAnalytics<br/> mu         sync.Mutex<br/>}</span></pre><p id="c6e6" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg">Each worker initializes its own local map and processes batches independently:</p><pre class="pp pq pr ps pt pu pv pw bl px ax bg"><span id="ba48" class="py on ho pv b bc pz qa e qb qc">func (p *Processor) ProcessStream(id int, lines &lt;-chan string, batchSize int) error {<br/> p.mu.Lock()<br/> p.workerMaps[id] = make(map[string]*UserAnalytics)<br/> p.mu.Unlock()<br/><br/> var batch []Transaction<br/><br/> for line := range lines {<br/>  var tx Transaction<br/>  if err := json.Unmarshal([]byte(line), &amp;tx); err != nil {<br/>   continue<br/>  }<br/><br/>  batch = append(batch, tx)<br/><br/>  if len(batch) &gt;= batchSize {<br/>   p.applyTransactions(id, batch)<br/>   batch = batch[:0]<br/>  }<br/> }<br/><br/> if len(batch) &gt; 0 {<br/>  p.applyTransactions(id, batch)<br/> }<br/><br/> return nil<br/>}</span></pre><p id="011d" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg">And the per-batch aggregation is straightforward:</p><pre class="pp pq pr ps pt pu pv pw bl px ax bg"><span id="9169" class="py on ho pv b bc pz qa e qb qc">func(p * Processor) applyTransactions(workerID int, txs[] Transaction) {<br/>    localMap: = p.workerMaps[workerID]<br/><br/>    for _,<br/>    tx: = range txs {<br/>        ua, ok: = localMap[tx.UserID]<br/>        if !ok {<br/>            ua = &amp; UserAnalytics {<br/>                UserID: tx.UserID<br/>            }<br/>            localMap[tx.UserID] = ua<br/>        }<br/><br/>        ua.TotalOrders++<br/>            ua.TotalSpent += tx.Price * float64(tx.Quantity)<br/>    }<br/>}</span></pre><p id="17bb" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg">The key property here is that each worker only touches its own map. No other worker reads or writes that data while processing is happening, so there is <strong class="nq hp">zero lock contention in the hot path</strong>.</p><p id="6c64" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg">When processing is done, we merge the worker-local maps into one final snapshot:</p><pre class="pp pq pr ps pt pu pv pw bl px ax bg"><span id="9634" class="py on ho pv b bc pz qa e qb qc">func (p *Processor) Snapshot() map[string]*UserAnalytics {<br/>      merged := make(map[string]*UserAnalytics)<br/><br/>      for _, workerMap := range p.workerMaps {<br/>          for userID, ua := range workerMap {<br/>              if existing, ok := merged[userID]; ok {<br/>                  existing.TotalOrders += ua.TotalOrders<br/>                  existing.TotalSpent += ua.TotalSpent<br/>              } else {<br/>                  merged[userID] = &amp;UserAnalytics{<br/>                      UserID:      ua.UserID,<br/>                      TotalOrders: ua.TotalOrders,<br/>                      TotalSpent:  ua.TotalSpent,<br/>                  }<br/>              }<br/>          }<br/>      }<br/><br/>      return merged<br/>}</span></pre><p id="8d77" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg">This is the real concurrency win.</p><p id="a67c" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg">Instead of making every transaction fight over shared memory, we let workers run independently and pay the coordination cost once at the end.</p><h2 id="3742" class="om on ho bb oo op oq or os ot ou ov ow ox oy oz pa pb pc pd pe pf pg ph pi pj bg">Putting It All Together</h2><p id="3100" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr pk nt nu nv pl nx ny nz pm ob oc od pn of og oh po oj ok ol hh bg">With all the pieces combined, the final pipeline looks like this:</p><ol class=""><li id="0df3" class="no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol qk ql qm bg">One goroutine reads the NDJSON file line by line.</li><li id="b8fe" class="no np ho nq b nr qn nt nu nv qo nx ny nz qp ob oc od qq of og oh qr oj ok ol qk ql qm bg">Lines are pushed into a buffered channel.</li><li id="7e96" class="no np ho nq b nr qn nt nu nv qo nx ny nz qp ob oc od qq of og oh qr oj ok ol qk ql qm bg">A worker pool parses transactions concurrently.</li><li id="366e" class="no np ho nq b nr qn nt nu nv qo nx ny nz qp ob oc od qq of og oh qr oj ok ol qk ql qm bg">Each worker batches transactions and updates its own private analytics map.</li><li id="faa2" class="no np ho nq b nr qn nt nu nv qo nx ny nz qp ob oc od qq of og oh qr oj ok ol qk ql qm bg">When processing completes, the worker-local maps are merged.</li><li id="f4ae" class="no np ho nq b nr qn nt nu nv qo nx ny nz qp ob oc od qq of og oh qr oj ok ol qk ql qm bg">The final aggregated result is flushed to PostgreSQL in bulk.</li></ol><p id="9abb" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg">That architecture matters because it keeps the hot path almost entirely in memory:</p><ul class=""><li id="b362" class="no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol qt ql qm bg">file reading is cheap and sequential</li><li id="e6c7" class="no np ho nq b nr qn nt nu nv qo nx ny nz qp ob oc od qq of og oh qr oj ok ol qt ql qm bg">parsing is spread across multiple cores</li><li id="89af" class="no np ho nq b nr qn nt nu nv qo nx ny nz qp ob oc od qq of og oh qr oj ok ol qt ql qm bg">analytics updates happen without shared-state contention</li><li id="d31e" class="no np ho nq b nr qn nt nu nv qo nx ny nz qp ob oc od qq of og oh qr oj ok ol qt ql qm bg">the database is touched once at the end instead of once per transaction</li></ul><p id="b734" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg">That last point is the biggest one. The main performance gain is not “<em class="qg">using goroutines.</em>” It’s moving database writes off the hot path and replacing a million small writes with a single bulk flush.</p><figure class="pp pq pr ps pt ne mw mx paragraph-image"><div role="button" tabindex="0" class="nf ng fv nh bd ni"><span class="ga gb gc ai gd ge gf fo gg speechify-ignore">Press enter or click to view image in full size</span><div class="mw mx tp"><picture><source srcSet="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*5uF9clg8eGfm9rSt4pNw5w.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*5uF9clg8eGfm9rSt4pNw5w.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*5uF9clg8eGfm9rSt4pNw5w.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*5uF9clg8eGfm9rSt4pNw5w.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*5uF9clg8eGfm9rSt4pNw5w.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*5uF9clg8eGfm9rSt4pNw5w.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/1*5uF9clg8eGfm9rSt4pNw5w.png 1400w" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" srcSet="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*5uF9clg8eGfm9rSt4pNw5w.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*5uF9clg8eGfm9rSt4pNw5w.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*5uF9clg8eGfm9rSt4pNw5w.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*5uF9clg8eGfm9rSt4pNw5w.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*5uF9clg8eGfm9rSt4pNw5w.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*5uF9clg8eGfm9rSt4pNw5w.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*5uF9clg8eGfm9rSt4pNw5w.png 1400w" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px"/><img alt="" class="bd md nj c" width="700" height="350" loading="lazy" role="presentation"/></picture></div></div><figcaption class="nk fj nl mw mx nm nn bb b bc u dy">The final pipeline</figcaption></figure><p id="c984" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg">Here’s how the configurations compare on 1 million transactions:</p><figure class="pp pq pr ps pt ne mw mx paragraph-image"><div role="button" tabindex="0" class="nf ng fv nh bd ni"><span class="ga gb gc ai gd ge gf fo gg speechify-ignore">Press enter or click to view image in full size</span><div class="mw mx tq"><picture><source srcSet="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*co4oVHpaNOwMJD0FbtQiDg.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*co4oVHpaNOwMJD0FbtQiDg.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*co4oVHpaNOwMJD0FbtQiDg.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*co4oVHpaNOwMJD0FbtQiDg.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*co4oVHpaNOwMJD0FbtQiDg.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*co4oVHpaNOwMJD0FbtQiDg.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/1*co4oVHpaNOwMJD0FbtQiDg.png 1400w" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" srcSet="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*co4oVHpaNOwMJD0FbtQiDg.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*co4oVHpaNOwMJD0FbtQiDg.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*co4oVHpaNOwMJD0FbtQiDg.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*co4oVHpaNOwMJD0FbtQiDg.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*co4oVHpaNOwMJD0FbtQiDg.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*co4oVHpaNOwMJD0FbtQiDg.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*co4oVHpaNOwMJD0FbtQiDg.png 1400w" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px"/><img alt="" class="bd md nj c" width="700" height="165" loading="lazy" role="presentation"/></picture></div></div><figcaption class="nk fj nl mw mx nm nn bb b bc u dy">Configuration comparison for 1 million transactions: 10 workers and a batch size of 500 performed best on my machine.</figcaption></figure><blockquote class="qd qe qf"><p id="c33c" class="no np qg nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg">These numbers were measured on a MacBook Pro M2 Pro. Your results will vary based on hardware, storage, and database setup. The relative behavior matters more than the exact number.</p></blockquote><p id="0d3a" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg">The default configuration is the sweet spot on my machine. Pushing the worker count higher doesn’t necessarily help. Past a certain point, scheduler overhead, memory traffic, and coordination cost outweigh the gains from more parallelism.</p><p id="2097" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg">Concurrency helps, but only when the architecture gives each worker useful independent work to do.</p><h2 id="bee6" class="om on ho bb oo op oq or os ot ou ov ow ox oy oz pa pb pc pd pe pf pg ph pi pj bg">What’s in Part 2</h2><p id="c0ea" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr pk nt nu nv pl nx ny nz pm ob oc od pn of og oh po oj ok ol hh bg">This was the proof of concept. We now know the core processing model works:</p><ul class=""><li id="ba3a" class="no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol qt ql qm bg">stream NDJSON instead of loading everything into memory</li><li id="e941" class="no np ho nq b nr qn nt nu nv qo nx ny nz qp ob oc od qq of og oh qr oj ok ol qt ql qm bg">spread parsing across a worker pool</li><li id="39ef" class="no np ho nq b nr qn nt nu nv qo nx ny nz qp ob oc od qq of og oh qr oj ok ol qt ql qm bg">aggregate in worker-local maps to avoid lock contention</li><li id="0d28" class="no np ho nq b nr qn nt nu nv qo nx ny nz qp ob oc od qq of og oh qr oj ok ol qt ql qm bg">bulk flush the final result to PostgreSQL</li></ul><p id="1573" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg">In <a class="z tr" href="https://medium.com/@kennedykaroko/processing-1-million-transactions-in-under-a-second-using-go-part-2-c075800fe7a4" rel="noopener">Part 2</a>, we’ll take that fast core and wrap it in a cleaner application structure: configuration, migrations, a repository layer, a service layer, Redis-backed reads, and an HTTP API for querying analytics.</p><p id="9786" class="pw-post-body-paragraph no np ho nq b nr ns nt nu nv nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg">The complete implementation is already on <a class="z tr" href="https://github.com/iamkaroko/tx-processor" rel="noopener ugc nofollow" target="_blank">GitHub</a> if you want to compare the proof of concept to the more structured version.</p><figure class="pp pq pr ps pt ne"><div class="qh ge e fv"><div class="ts qj e"></div></div></figure></div></div></div></div></section></div></div></article></div><div class="v cf"><div class="cm bd gt gu gv gw"><div class="tt tu v jl"><div class="tl v"><a class="tv ae ai ak" href="https://medium.com/tag/golang?source=post_page-----98c9079375ac---------------------------------------" rel="noopener follow"><div class="si fv db tw gy tx ty bb b bc u bg fo">Golang</div></a></div><div class="tl v"><a class="tv ae ai ak" href="https://medium.com/tag/concurrency?source=post_page-----98c9079375ac---------------------------------------" rel="noopener follow"><div class="si fv db tw gy tx ty bb b bc u bg fo">Concurrency</div></a></div><div class="tl v"><a class="tv ae ai ak" href="https://medium.com/tag/backend?source=post_page-----98c9079375ac---------------------------------------" rel="noopener follow"><div class="si fv db tw gy tx ty bb b bc u bg fo">Backend</div></a></div><div class="tl v"><a class="tv ae ai ak" href="https://medium.com/tag/postgresql?source=post_page-----98c9079375ac---------------------------------------" rel="noopener follow"><div class="si fv db tw gy tx ty bb b bc u bg fo">Postgresql</div></a></div><div class="tl v"><a class="tv ae ai ak" href="https://medium.com/tag/distributed-systems?source=post_page-----98c9079375ac---------------------------------------" rel="noopener follow"><div class="si fv db tw gy tx ty bb b bc u bg fo">Distributed Systems</div></a></div></div></div></div><div class="e"></div><footer class="tz ua ub uc ud v j ue uf c"><div class="e y"><div class="v cf"><div class="cm bd gt gu gv gw"><div class="v ct ug"><div class="v j ku"><div class="uh e"><span class="e ui uj uk ul s"><div class="v j ku kv"><div class="pw-multi-vote-icon fv kw kx ky kz"><span data-dd-action-name="Susi presentation tracker clap_footer"><a class="z ab ac fl af ag ah ai aj ak al am an ao ap" data-testid="footerClapButton" href="https://medium.com/m/signin?actionUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2F_%2Fvote%2Fp%2F98c9079375ac&amp;operation=register&amp;redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fblog.karoko.dev%2Fprocessing-1-million-transactions-in-under-a-second-using-go-part-1-98c9079375ac&amp;user=Kennedy+Karoko&amp;userId=eb4faf0972a&amp;source=---footer_actions--98c9079375ac---------------------clap_footer------------------" rel="noopener follow"><div><div class="bi" role="tooltip"><div tabindex="-1" class="ba"><div class="la ak lb lc ld le ai lf lg lh kz" role="presentation"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" aria-label="clap"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M11.37.828 12 3.282l.63-2.454zM13.916 3.953l1.523-2.112-1.184-.39zM8.589 1.84l1.522 2.112-.337-2.501zM18.523 18.92c-.86.86-1.75 1.246-2.62 1.33a6 6 0 0 0 .407-.372c2.388-2.389 2.86-4.951 1.399-7.623l-.912-1.603-.79-1.672c-.26-.56-.194-.98.203-1.288a.7.7 0 0 1 .546-.132c.283.046.546.231.728.5l2.363 4.157c.976 1.624 1.141 4.237-1.324 6.702m-10.999-.438L3.37 14.328a.828.828 